Here is why Cardano will soon surpass Bitcoin !

@IOHK_Charles  the founder of #Cardano, recently expressed his belief that #Cardano ( $ADA ) could surpass #Bitcoin ( $BTC ) in terms of market capitalization. In a podcast, Hoskinson highlighted Bitcoin’s limitations and emphasized Cardano’s innovative capabilities...

Bitcoin Soon Obsolete ?

According to Hoskinson, Bitcoin, while being the first and largest cryptocurrency, suffers from a lack of innovation. He compares Bitcoin to obsolete platforms like Yahoo and MySpace, which were surpassed by more advanced technologies...

Hoskinson claims that Bitcoin is resting on its laurels, focusing more on its size and past success rather than developing new features. He adds, “Bitcoin is dead in the water. The only value proposition it has is that it is big and successful. That’s it.”

#Cardano’s Formidable Weapons :

On the other hand, Cardano stands out for its innovative approach and ability to integrate new technologies. Hoskinson explained that the #Cardano ecosystem is designed to evolve and adapt, allowing it to meet the changing needs of the market. He also emphasized the importance of the Cardano community, which plays a crucial role in the platform’s development and adoption...

One of Cardano’s main strengths lies in its ability to offer smart contracts and decentralized applications (dApps) more efficiently and securely than Bitcoin. Hoskinson mentioned that #Cardano was designed from the start to be a flexible and scalable platform capable of adapting to future technological advancements...

Hoskinson also addressed the issue of sustainability. Unlike Bitcoin, which uses an energy-intensive proof-of-work (PoW) model, Cardano uses a much more energy-efficient proof-of-stake (PoS) model. This approach not only reduces Cardano’s carbon footprint but also makes it more attractive to environmentally conscious investors...

Finally, while Bitcoin is currently the market leader, Hoskinson is convinced that Cardano has the potential to surpass it through continuous innovation, a dynamic community, and a sustainable model. Only time will tell if Cardano can indeed dethrone Bitcoin, but the prospects are promising for this growing platform...

text:
Wondering where we are at with *Babel Fees* for #Cardano?  

We just introduced the *validation zones* CIP that describes an on-chain mechanism allowing for underspecified transactions like swap requests to be bundled together and validated as a unit:  https://t.co/RvLDHfgpHY.

Congrats @polinavinovino, @mpeytonjones, Will and the rest of @InputOutputHK R&D team (IOR) who worked on this innovation work stream 🖖 

In short, the proposal aims to support more flexible intent settlement on Cardano in several key ways:
- It introduces the concept of validation zones, which allow multiple related transactions to be bundled and validated together. This enables atomic swaps and other complex operations that require multiple steps.
- It adds new transaction fields for "requests" and "fulfills", allowing users to express intents (like swap offers) without immediately executing them.

Let's take an example to see how this enables babel fees✍️ 

Imagine that:
1. A user creates transaction tx1 with:
-  no $ADA inputs
- A request for X $ADA (enough to cover transaction fees)
- An unlocked output containing Y TokenX (as an offer to compensate for the Ada)
2. The user sends tx1 to a facilitator through some off-chain mechanism
3. The facilitator creates two transactions, 
- tx2: fulfills the request for X Ada from tx1, and requires tx3
- tx3: spends the unlocked output containing Y TokenX from tx1
4. The facilitator submits a validation zone consisting of bundling  tx1, tx2 and tx3.

In this scenario:
- tx1 represents the user's intent to pay fees in TokenX
- tx2 provides the Ada for fees
- tx3 collects the TokenX offered as compensation
- The validation zone ensures atomicity of the swap.

The CIP  links to the formal specs and prototype (not production-ready indeed), if you want to dig in:
-https://t.co/bsRa6CMTxa
- https://t.co/JKJsHYKOg2

text:
With the release of #Cardano Node 9.1 and publication of the Conway Genesis file, it is my pleasure to share this report of the @IntersectMBO Governance Parameters Working Group.

➡️https://t.co/GY7Kol5kNk

This group was formed to ensure there would be community input into setting the initial governance parameters of Cardano as we implement CIP-1694 and transition into Voltaire governance. The process started by looking at the Cardano community feedback given in the CIP-1694 workshops, moved on to conduct a community-wide survey facilitated by @SummonPlatform and @DripDropz_io, and was then finalized in discussion between the Governance Parameter Working Group and the full Parameters Committee of Intersect MBO. 

This report would not have been possible without the hard work of my fellow members of the working group: Nicolas Cerny @NicolasC3rny of @Cardano_CF, Jenny Brito @Jennycitalinda, Oscar Hong @OscarW3st, Mike Hornan @Hornan7, Jonathan Kelly @intertreeJK, and Riley Kilgore @ILikeCardano.

We also wish to acknowledge the help we received from intersect MBO in facilitating our group and the invaluable consultations from Kevin Hammond @khstandrews and Sam Leathers @therealdisasm of @IOG_Eng, Sheldon Hunt @_MrHunt_ of @emurgo_io, Michael Madoff @michael_madoff of @InputOutputHK, and Eric Alston @IncompleteRules of @block_science.

These governance parameters are not meant to be the final governing protocol of Cardano or permanent parameters, by any means. They are being recommended for the minimum viable governance of Cardano as we prepare to move into a new era of community-led control and development of the network.

It is our desire and expectation that the community will conscientiously deliberate and build on these parameters moving forward. We hope that the background of thoughts and ideas we offer in this report will be of help in that process.

text:
What TPS will #Cardano achieve with Ouroboros Leios?

I know that TPS is not an ideal metric for Cardano.

A Cardano block is currently 90,112 bytes in size. 

A typical transaction is roughly 300 bytes (although this can vary based on the number of input and output UTxOs). 

The current block can hold approximately 300 transactions. 

Since Cardano mints a new block every 20 seconds, the current throughput is around 15 TPS.

If the block contained larger, 16,000-byte transactions, roughly 6 would fit into the block. Each such transaction could contain up to 250 outputs (recipients). 

A value can be sent to up to 1500 recipients in one block, resulting in 75 TPS.

In Ouroboros Leios, throughput will depend on the size and minting rate of Input Blocks (IBs). 

The current blocks will become the Ranking Blocks.

IBs are data carriers and are expected to be minted between 0.2 and 2 seconds. 

Initially, the minting rate will be set conservatively and may scale down as needed to increase throughput.

The Input Block can have the same size as the current blocks, but theoretically, it's possible to increase them if the network can handle data diffusion quickly. 

As the block size increases, the throughput will also increase. 

Similarly to the minting rate, the block size will likely start conservatively and grow only if there is demand for higher scalability. 

The limit for increasing the block size is the Total Delay (explained in the previous tweets).

A larger number of Input Blocks means more references in Endorsement Blocks (EBs). 

The size of EBs will also increase. Diffusing EBs and RBs requires a certain amount of network capacity.

In a theoretical scenario with the largest block size (it is 2000 KB in the table) and the lowest minting rate of IBs (0.2 seconds), Cardano could achieve up to 80,000 TPS. 

However, these ambitious numbers may result in slow distribution and referencing challenges.

A more practical approach would be to keep the block size at 90 KB and the minting rate at 0.2 seconds (5 Input Blocks per second). 

In this case, Cardano could achieve around 1500 TPS, which is more realistic and still a significant improvement.

Remember that these numbers are theoretical and subject to real-world constraints. 

Cardano's actual throughput will depend on various factors, including technical limitations and further innovations.

#Cardano fam, I’ll say this. 

The crypto markets are very predatory. With professional HF day trading desks, exchanges, and now the Blackrock & Fidelity’s of the world, the level of difficulty of the game has risen to a whole new level.

Understand this though, at the fundamental level their greatest weapon to effect price for the purposes of accumulation or distribution is based around manipulating the human emotions of market participants, primarily “dumb” money, or in other words us Retail.

They do this in many ways from raw price action where they short on futures while accumulating spot (for example) or they use their bought and paid for media outlets to put out either bearish or bullish stories to control the narrative.
